<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="418" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,1702,1904]" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1769,1794]" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">Comments</emphasis>
. This very small species (
<quantity box="[625,715,1769,1793]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="418" unit="mm" value="0.7">0.7 mm</quantity>
) is characterized by the wings with a wedge-shaped base and a reduced anal area, an isolated base of CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[627,635,1820,1834]" fontSize="6" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">1</subScript>
and CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[741,749,1820,1834]" fontSize="6" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">2</subScript>
, and the gonostylus pointed towards the apex, with 3 densely grouped apical spines. The female is fully winged, the eye bridge 1–2 facets wide with loosely arranged ommatidia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
